Context¶

Normally, this is where I make up a fake backstory to present context and an excuse to justify this analysis.

Not this time! We don't have time to create elaborate plot twists, secret romances, and stories of betrayal (this week).

We have just learned about linear regression and I am dying to regress some data linearly and try out all of these magical things.

Our approach¶

For this project, I want to deep dive into the implementation aspect of things:

  • I want to compare various approaches to perform linear (and non-linear regression)
    • and I want to use statistical analysis tools to assess how they perform
  • I want to explore:
    • automated approaches to feature engineering
    • automated (statistical) approaches to feature selection
    • manual (=brute-force) approaches to linear regression model creation
    • and compare them with their automated counterparts
  • I want to compare, assess and visualize:
    • their requirements
    • their performance
    • their cost (timing/compute)

Since this is all quite new to me, I want to make my own custom-made Smörgåsbord of linear regression approaches, tools and methodologies.

With this plan on the table, we are ready to start!

Some indicators of wine quality include complexity, balance, typicity (how much the wine looks and tastes the way it should), intensity and finish. E> the only fields I have are ['fixed acidity', 'volatile acidity', 'citric acid', 'residual sugar', 'chlorides', 'free sulfur dioxide', 'total sulfur dioxide', 'density', 'pH', 'sulphates', 'alcohol', 'quality']... what can you tell me about those?

ChatGPT> These fields are physicochemical properties of wine that can be used to predict its quality.

  1. Fixed acidity refers to the concentration of tartaric acid, which is one of the main acids found in wine.
  2. Volatile acidity refers to the concentration of acetic acid, which can give wine a vinegar-like taste if present in high concentrations.
  3. Citric acid is another acid found in wine that can affect its taste.
  4. Residual sugar refers to the amount of sugar remaining in wine after fermentation has stopped.
  5. Chlorides can affect the saltiness of wine.
  6. Free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide refer to the amount of sulfur dioxide present in wine, which acts as a preservative and antioxidant.
  7. Density is a measure of how much matter is contained within a given volume and can be affected by factors such as alcohol content and sugar content.
  8. pH measures how acidic or basic a solution is on a scale from 0-14 (with 7 being neutral).
  9. Sulphates are salts that can be formed when sulfuric acid reacts with another chemical and can affect taste and color stability.
  10. Alcohol content affects many aspects of wine including taste, mouthfeel, and aroma.

[end of transcript]

Building our first (custom-made) pipeline¶

We want to create a simple back-of-the-envelope pipeline that will give us:

  • READABILITY: it should describe the steps we are going through
    • we want to separate the WHAT we are doing (which matters) from the HOW (which most of the time is boring and irrelevant)
    • it also allows anyone to focus deeply into the HOWs if we notice weird stuff (eg. suddenly we dropped too many values! or if a particular step is too slow!)
  • OBSERVABILITY: it should provide crude monitoring so we get insights into what's happening in each step (duration, data we keep, changes in our data, etc..)
  • EXTENSIBILITY: since we envision that this is very generalizable, we also want to be able to add additional custom inspections into each of the steps (where necessary)

Using linear regression models to make predictions¶

Two of the primary requirements for this project are to:

  • Apply linear machine learning models to predict the quality column using the other 11 features
  • Apply linear machine learning models to predict the alcohol column using the other 11 features

Now. While we know that using all 11 features will likely give us the best prediction score, it is also true that it will be:

  • slower to train
  • more expensive (more computing resources)
  • and it will likely reach a point of diminishing returns.

I want to explore the cost-benefit of the suggested approach and find the sweet spot where we can get the best bang for our proverbial computing buck.

Ideally, what is the min number of features we need to use in our training to get the best benefit-cost ratio (i.e. the success_rate -to- training_time)

In order to compare like-with-like algorithms/models, we want to use the same approach:

How to split the data:

  • training data: 70%
  • test data: 30%

How to measure timing:

  • timing: train the model + (1 pass of predictions)

Iteration 1 - The easy/cheap baseline (AutoFeat)¶

We want to start with the cheapest way to get a "guaranteed" out-of-the-box success...

For this, we want to hit:

  • the most out-of-the-box experience/library
  • the smallest amount of work (for us)
    • ideally, it should use an algorithm that takes in all the features and decides which to keep and which to drop, without requiring us to make any decisions
  • give it all the features and see what it does
  • fundamentallty: we expect that this ready-to-use library will make some opaque decisions and keep the complexities away from us

What we want to measure:

  • How good the predictions are, using $R^2$ (regression), and accuracy (classification).
  • How long it takes to train the model and make predictions (1 pass)

Predicting Alcohol¶

Let's create a small factory method that will ensure all instances created in this notebook have some common settings:

  • 8 threads
    • SO THAT we can leverage multi-core CPUs
  • Disable all of the "advanced" transformations ('1/', 'exp', 'log', 'abs', 'sqrt', '^2', '^3'), which are enabled by default
    • SO THAT we remove unnecessary transformations, since these are not needed and they would make the regression non-linear.
In [266]:
def AutoFeatRegressor(*args, **kwargs):
    """
    custom wrapper that ensures we always
    spin up 8 threads for better performance.

    8 is the number of cores in this PC and has been
    empirically tested to be a good balance
    1 thread ~= 80 seconds
    8 threads ~= 20 seconds
    """
    kwargs["n_jobs"] = 8
    disable_advanced_transformations = ()
    return AFR(transformations=disable_advanced_transformations, *args, **kwargs)

We are ready to start, but something happened when training this model. Our randomization seed caused some minor problems. So we picked a different one.

Here's the long version of what happened:

If we set the random_state=0, we end up with a peculiar situation:

The training dataset accidentally/randomly ends up with no values of '0' in the citric_acid column. This results in the model thinking that there will never be 0s in that col, and it fails to discard derived features that rely on that assumption (eg. $citric\_acid^2*log(citric\_acid)$).

When we try to use our test portion of the data, for one of the rows, this new feature ends up being NaN due to the $log(0)$ part, and makes other calculations crash.

There would be multiple ways to handle this:

  • replacing 0s with values very close to 0 (eg. 1e-10)
  • adjusting further..

But these seemed like hacky approaches. The solution that seems to correct this better is to make sure that the training set and the test set both contain representative data of the real world. That means, using a different split (which is determined by the specific random seed) that somewhat separates our test data and our training data in a way to ends up being more representative. Using a random_state=1 did the trick, so I didn't check beyond that seed.

I also noticed that instead of 29 features, this time we end up with 24. My understanding is that some of those 5 features we lost were going to be problematic for the same reason (the 2 datasets not being representative of each other or the real world)

Important clarification¶

This new features are not linear. .

Even though we actively disabled the more complex transformations in our custom AutoFeat() factory method, above, this regression is still non linear because some of the newly generated features are polynomial.

  • Multiplication between factors results in a vector space that is non-linear.
  • For regression to be linear, we are only allowed to use $+$ summation:
    • recall: linear algebra, where we define a vector space using independent unitary vectors. We can use this to create a space and allows us to then define any point in that space as a sum of scaled vectors $3\vec{u} + 5\vec{v}$

Alright, so.. technically, this model is not linear. However, I decided to try it out:

  • because I wanted to see how to use AutoFeat
  • and because in the rest of the notebook, we will explore actual linear regression, and we will be comparing those results, to these ones.

The chart looks like what we'd imagine for a categorical-like variable prediction, with a peak around integers (-2, -1, 0, 1, 2...)

We can see a few differences with the previous run:

  • The score is much smaller (~0.80 vs ~0.38) than before
  • The 95% confidence interval is also wider (range of ~2.5 vs range of ~0.45)

Since the values for the dataset were already normalize, the change in the spread of the confidence interval is not due to them having different scales/ranges. It must be due to the worse performance.

I suspect that this is lower score when predicting Quality (compared to Alcohol) must be caused by the nature of the data itself.

  • Alcohol is a continuous variable.
  • Quality is represented as an int, and it's fundamentally discrete (even categorical, if we wanted to squint our eyes a little bit and)

This means that, when trying to predict alcohol, our model is allowed to output floats, and the difference is rather small. But when we try to predict quality, our model is trying to make predictions for each of the categories and, but the small granularity means that a mistake is never "oh, so close!".

I think that if we had a dataset that allowed quality to have decimal places, our model would be able to both learn better, and also predict better.

Iteration 2 - Minimal effort (SelectKBest)¶

The rest of the iterations (parts 2 and 3) will all revolve around different approaches to predicting one of the attributes, just to reduce the amount of time and processing. But the method would be the same for any other feature.

We will use Alcohol as we've seen that it is easier to find a stronger model.

In this iteration we will use SelectKBest to compare how different numbers of features affect the strength of the model.

We expect to see a pareto-like distribution, where we get most of the boost with the first few K attributes, and then we hit a point of diminishing returns where each new feature only improves the model marginally.

diffs_df = pd.DataFrame(results).loc[diffs]

def plotkde(ax, row, col, i):
    if i > 10:
        return False
    data = diffs_df.iloc[i].values
    charts.kde_with_ci(data, ci=0.95, ax=ax)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 5)
    ax.set_xlim(-0.4, 0.4)
    ax.set_title(f"k = {i+1}")


charts.grid(3, 4, plotkde, (12, 5))
plt.tight_layout()
__

Errors for [Select K Best] attributes

Over these transitions, as we increase the $K$ value to select more and more attributes, we can see that:

  • The errors tend to concentrate over the 0.0 point (startig around $-0.2$ and ending at $-0.02$)
  • The error density tends to increase at the center of the curve (starting at $0.25$ down to $0.42$)
  • The 95% confidence interval tends to get narrower (starting at a range of $0,551$ down to $0,357$)

Regarding Overfitting¶

Somewhere in this transition, there seems to be a transition from "improving performance" to "overfitting the model".

I am not sure how to detect that progressive threshold that transitions from one behaviour to the other, but it would be nice to learn how to spot it so we can make informed decisions.

If I had to guess, just based on the shape of the curve, I'd say k=7 seems to be the ideal spot. The curves after that start to deviate away from the general shape of a normal gauss curve.

After multiple runs, this chart keeps changing. It's hard to derive hard conclusions from this chart, since lots of factors could affect it. In general, and most of the times:

  • the larger K gets the larger duration is.
  • however, there are so many small noisy factors that the change is not visible with such a small dataset:
    • cpu overhead
    • cpu scheduling algorithms
    • resources allocation/deallocation
    • cpu optimizations (caching...)
    • OS process optimizations
    • even the number of times we rerun this over and over, affects caching strategies

While we cannot categorically claim that duration increases with such a small dataset, it's expected that it would, for a larger dataset where computing more features would require more time (in a more noticeable way)

Iteration 3 - The Grind (Brute forcing all the combinations)¶

The last approach we wanted to try was to brute-force all the combinations so we could compare this approach to the previous two.

The previous two approaches use statistical methods to determine the ideal features to select, before performing the regression.

The first one even uses them to create new features and then decide which ones to keep.

With this analysis, we want to see how much worse is the performance if we decide to select categories without applying well known shortcuts to reduce processing time

Approach¶

We will generate lots of models with different features and use OLS to fit different models. Then we'll use $R^2$ and compute power to compare their cost-benefit

We expect something similar will happen (point of diminishing returns) once we start including more and more features.

However, just like in the previous example, it's unlikely that the curve will be obvious, considering that the dataset is so small.

Summary¶

In this study we have used explored:

  • AutoFeat for its versatility (Feature Engineering, Feature Selection, and Linear Regression modelling)
  • SkLearn for Linear Regression Modelling
  • OLS for calculating Ordinary Least Squares in our brute-force methodology.

Lessons Learned & Technical Concerns¶

  • Regarding the Methodology and Tools:

    • SelectKBest provides the simplest approach, in terms of explainability, to linear regression. The only input it requires is the number of features to use. It uses statistical tools to select the features that affect the result the most, in order to reduce computational efforts and end-to-end time.
    • AutoFeat tries to simplify things further by automatically deciding the number of features to include as well. In terms of compute power and time, there's a notable investment in generating features and in selecting the top-contributors.
    • The Brute-force approach requires a lot more time, but has several drawbacks:
      • It does not use statistical tools to try to find which features contribute the most to the target.
      • It requires an exhaustive approach to cover all combinations of features.
      • Even though, right now it takes a similar amount of time as AutoFeat(25 seconds vs 27 seconds), it's obvious that with a larger dataset, this approach would not scale up.

  • Regarding Scaling/descaling values:

    • MinMaxScaler provides a inverse_transform() to undo the changes, but it's important to remember that it should be trained/fit with the same original data first.
    • Once we perform operations on values that have been scaled (eg. difference), those can no longer be descaled back, and attempting to do it will result in values in a scale that does not make sense.
    • The safe way to do so is to: Predict, Descale, Diff instead of Predict, Diff, Descale

  • Regarding overfitting:

    • In all 3 methodologies, we used a 70%/30% split between training and testing data, to avoid overfitting.
    • While this study does not cover the detection of overfitting, it seems to be present in some of the results, although this is only a perception, and not based on any data.
    • Larger $R^2$ should not be favoured blindly, and given the same results/performance we should prefer:
      • simpler models
      • more explainable models
      • faster/cheaper

  • What to pick in the future, based on what we observed:

    • Select K Best was very easy to use and provides the easiest to understand models.
    • AutoFeat provides similar performance, but generates new features, which might not make sense, or might be expensive to compute for larger datasets.
    • Exhaustive/brute force should never be used for datasets beyond 2 rows and 2 columns.

Conclusions¶

Executive Summary¶

This study uses the wine dataset available in kaggle uciml/red-wine-quality-cortez-et-al-2009.

This dataset is relatively small, and has no missing data, making it ideal for simple models that require datasets with no missing values.

In this study we have assessed, compared and explored various ways to perform linear regression (and non-linear regression).

Some of the dimensions we explored: quality, fit, performance, cost can be useful to get a general understanding of these tools, but should not be taken as extrapolable rules for larger datasets, as they don't all scale equally.

In general, we should favour methods that have built-in optimizations (statistical methods) to determine the more relevant features to pick, as these will greatly reduce the time needed and the expensive computations required to reach acceptable results.

Future Work¶

  1. Something that could have been done to go more in depth would be to try various models of logistic regression to try to predict each of the values in "quality"
  2. AutoFeat is specialized for scientific analysis and allows users to specify the units of each column. This allows the library to not generate features that do not make sense (eg. ${car\_price + number\_of\_doors^2} - {miles\_per\_gallon}$). Maybe in future analysis this could be leveraged to skip nonsensical features that might lead to overfitting.
  3. In the future, I'd like to explore IPyWidgets in more depth, but there are 2 things that are holding me back
    1. The API has changed recently, and there are lots of outdated examples online.
    2. the documentation is one of the few places with reliable information, but that requires a notable investment.
    3. The rendering and interactivity is lost for readers who use a prerendered version (html), which is something I've been trying to prioritize. Readers should get the entire experiene/story without having to pip install or run anything locally.
